DMTV Milkshake: Mastering the Art of ‘Interior Marketing’ \\\
For this week’s Milkshake, we spoke to @leiatward, founder and principal of home staging firm @ltwdesign. Selling a house? Buying a house? Wondering about the “one weird trick” of staging a home? Leia has the inside scoop on how to max out your asking price — even if it means a change-up from your beloved trad decor to something more … transitional, plus why you’re going to have to say goodbye to those rugs (at least for a moment). \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

Featuring a vessel from @angusandceleste! \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

node.text: After discovering this summerhouse while on a walk about an hour outside of Copenhagen in 2017, @mariehesseldahl fell in love with the architecture and the way it blended with the natural environment. The one-story, wooden “type house” was designed by renowned Danish architects Knud Friis & Elmar Moltke Nielsen of Friis & Moltke in the mid 60s and when the original owner saw the design in an architectural magazine in 1969, he had it built on a pine plantation in North Zealand, Denmark. While simple, the house is dotted with special original details and materials including pine veneer wall paneling, black ceiling beams and built-in furniture. Not everyone would appreciate this mid-century gem the way Hesseldahl did, but as a designer and Design Manager for Danish brand Muuto, it couldn't have ended up in better hands. \\\ Read more about this Danish summer house at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: Release the Kraken! 🐙 Architect, artist and process designer Oskar Zięta recently brought the legendary sea creature to life inside of the Museum of Gdańsk. The sculpture consists of an almost four-meter head, which is connected to eight tentacles, each 5-10 meters long! Zięta's steel sculpture will hang over visitors’ heads at the Artus Court until November 2021. Get more details at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: No matter the weather, you can always enjoy nature while you’re indoors by adding potted plants throughout your space. If you live in a small home with limited floor space, going vertical with hanging planters is a great option. Even with all the room in the world, raising plants off the floor or tables turns them into living three-dimensional displays. \\\ Ready to add some hanging planters to your space? Take a look at six of our favorites that will transform your space at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: Verandah Place Townhouse is a minimal residence located in Brooklyn, New York, designed by @space4architecture. The building’s origin, a carriage house, dates back to the late 1800s, and throughout time, many of its original details have been stripped away, leaving only the framework. This allowed the architects to create a new space within the open framework of the narrow historic building \\\ In this week's Skim Milk, see how this old carriage house was transformed for a young family. Link in bio. 🔗
